Definition Definition 1.3.4 Consider the based ring $M_{n,\Gamma,B}$. We associate to the sequence $(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n})$ of grouplike elements of $B$ the based ring automorphism ${\beta}={\beta}(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n})$ of $M_{n,\Gamma,B}$. This is defined to send the element $X\in M_{n,\Gamma,B}$ to $G^{-1}XG$, where $G=\sum_{i=1}^{n}e_{ii}\otimes b_{i}.$ (This makes sense by Lemma 1.2.2.) The automorphism ${\beta}$ will be twisted unless all the $b_{i}$ are equal. If $w$ is a permutation in the symmetric group ${\Cal{S}}(n)$, we define an untwisted based ring automorphism, ${\sigma}_{w}$, of $M_{n,\Gamma,B}$ that sends $e_{ij}\otimes b$ to $e_{w^{-1}i,w^{-1}j}\otimes b$. If ${\varepsilon}$ is a based ring automorphism of $(\Gamma,B)$ (not necessarily one of the form given in Lemma 1.2.2 (ii)), we define an untwisted based ring automorphism $\psi_{\varepsilon}$ of $M_{n,\Gamma,B}$ by $\psi_{\varepsilon}(e_{ij}\otimes b)=e_{ij}\otimes{\varepsilon}(b)$.
Definition Definition 3.1.2 Let $A$ be a reduced tabular algebra with trace and with tabular basis ${\mathbb{B}}$. Let $(\Lambda,\Gamma,B,M,C,*)$ be a table datum for $A$. The based poset $P(A,{\mathbb{B}})=P(\Lambda,\Gamma,B,M,C,*)=P(\Lambda,\Gamma,B,M,*)$ associated to the table datum $(\Lambda,\Gamma,B,M,C,*)$ is the triple $(\Lambda,\leq,f)$ where $(\Lambda,\leq)$ is the poset in the table datum of $A$ and, for each ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$, $f({\lambda})$ is the based ring $M_{|M({\lambda})|,\Gamma({\lambda}),B({\lambda})}\cong A_{\lambda}^{\infty}$. Such a based poset is equipped with an anti-automorphism, $*$, which by definition leaves the elements of the poset fixed and induces the map $*$ of Lemma 1.2.4 (ii) on each $f({\lambda})$. The category ${\Cal{P}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$ has as objects all elements $P(D)$ for $D\in{\Cal{D}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$ (see Definition 2.4.1); the morphisms are isomorphisms of based posets.
Definition Definition 1.2.3 Let $(\Gamma,B)$ be a normalized table algebra. The based ring $M_{n,\Gamma,B}$ is the ring of $n\times n$ matrices over the ring $\Gamma$, equipped with distinguished basis consisting of all elements $e_{ij}\otimes b$, where $e_{ij}$ is a matrix unit and $b\in B$. We call the elements $e_{ii}\otimes 1$ (for $1\leq i\leq n$) distinguished idempotents.
Definition Definition 2.3.2 Let $A$ be a tabular algebra. If $X$ and $X^{\prime}$ are tabular basis elements, we say that $X^{\prime}\preceq X$ if $X^{\prime}$ appears with nonzero coefficient in $KXK^{\prime}$ for some tabular basis elements $K,K^{\prime}$. The relation $\preceq$ on the tabular basis $\text{\rm Im}(C)$ is defined to be the transitive extension of this relation; it is reflexive by axiom (A1).
Definition Definition 1.2.1 A based ring is a pair $(A,B)$, where $A$ is a unital ${\mathbb{Z}}$-algebra with free ${\mathbb{Z}}$-basis $B$ and nonnegative structure constants. A homomorphism $\phi:(A,B){\ \longrightarrow\ }(A^{\prime},B^{\prime})$ of based rings is a homomorphism of abstract ${\mathbb{Z}}$-algebras $\phi:A{\ \longrightarrow\ }A^{\prime}$ such that $\phi(b)\in B^{\prime}\cup\{0\}$ for all $b\in B$. Isomorphisms, automorphisms etc. of based rings are defined analogously.
Definition Definition 2.1.1 Let ${\Cal{A}}$ be the ring of Laurent polynomials ${\mathbb{Z}}[v,v^{-1}]$, let $A$ be an ${\Cal{A}}$-algebra and let ${\mathbb{B}}$ be an ${\Cal{A}}$-basis of $A$. For $X,Y,Z\in{\mathbb{B}}$, we define the structure constants $g_{X,Y,Z}\in{\Cal{A}}$ by the formula $XY=\sum_{Z}g_{X,Y,Z}Z.$ The a-function is defined by ${\text{\bf a}}(Z)=\max_{X,Y\in{\mathbb{B}}}\deg(g_{X,Y,Z}),$ where the degree of a Laurent polynomial is taken to be the highest power of $v$ occurring with nonzero coefficient. We define ${\gamma}_{X,Y,Z}\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ to be the coefficient of $v^{{\text{\bf a}}(Z)}$ in $g_{X,Y,Z}$; this will be zero if the bound is not achieved.
Definition Definition 4.2.5 For $1\leq a<b\leq n$, we define the basis elements $e_{a,b}$ and $g_{a,b}$ of $B_{n}$ as follows. For the element $e_{a,b}$, point $j$ in row $1$ is joined to point $j$ in row $2$, unless $j\in\{a,b\}$. Points $a$ and $b$ in row $i$ (for $i\in\{1,2\}$) are joined to each other. For the element $g_{a,b}$, point $j$ in row $1$ is joined to point $j$ in row $2$, unless $j\in\{a,b\}$. Point $a$ in row $i$ is joined to point $b$ in row $3-i$ (for $i\in\{1,2\}$).
Definition Definition 3.1.3 Let $A$ be a reduced tabular algebra with trace and tabular basis ${\mathbb{B}}$. Let $D$ be an object of ${\Cal{D}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$ and let $P(D)$ be the corresponding object of ${\Cal{P}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$. A parametrization of $D$ consists of bijections $s_{\lambda}:M({\lambda}){\ \longrightarrow\ }\{1,2,\ldots,|M({\lambda})|\}$ and a map $\pi:\coprod_{\lambda}\left(M({\lambda})\times B({\lambda})\times M({\lambda})% \right){\ \longrightarrow\ }\coprod_{{\lambda}\in\Lambda}f({\lambda})$ such that for all ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$, $S,T\in M({\lambda})$ and $b\in B({\lambda})$, $\pi(S,b,T)=e_{s_{\lambda}(S),s_{\lambda}(T)}\otimes b\in f({\lambda})$. We will typically refer to the parametrization $(\pi,\ \coprod_{{\lambda}\in\Lambda}s_{\lambda})$ as “the parametrization $\pi$” for short.
Definition Definition 1.3.2 Let ${\alpha}:M_{n,\Gamma,B}{\ \longrightarrow\ }M_{n^{\prime},\Gamma^{\prime},B^{% \prime}}$ be a homomorphism of based rings. If there exist a map ${\sigma}:\{1,\ldots,n\}{\ \longrightarrow\ }\{1,\ldots,n^{\prime}\}$ and a homomorphism of based rings $\psi:(\Gamma,B){\ \longrightarrow\ }(\Gamma^{\prime},B^{\prime})$ such that ${\alpha}(e_{ij}\otimes b)=e_{{\sigma}(i){\sigma}(j)}\otimes\psi(b)$ for all $1\leq i,j\leq n$ and $b\in B$ then we call ${\alpha}$ an untwisted homomorphism. Otherwise, we call ${\alpha}$ a twisted homomorphism.
Definition Definition 3.2.1 Let $(\Lambda,\leq,f)$ and $(\Pi,\leq^{\prime},g)$ be objects of ${\Cal{P}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$. Let $p_{\Lambda}:\Lambda{\ \longrightarrow\ }\Pi$ be an isomorphism of abstract posets, and for each ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$ let $p_{\lambda}$ be an untwisted isomorphism of based rings (see Definition 1.3.2) from $f({\lambda})$ to $g(p_{\Lambda}({\lambda}))$. We define the isomorphism of based posets $\iota_{p}:(\Lambda,\leq,f){\ \longrightarrow\ }(\Pi,\leq^{\prime},g)$ to be the isomorphism inducing the map $p_{\Lambda}$ on $\Lambda$ and the maps $p_{\lambda}$ on each $f({\lambda})$. Let $(\Lambda,\leq,f)$ be an object of ${\Cal{P}}(A,{\mathbb{B}})$, let ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$ and set $n=|M({\lambda})|$. Let ${\beta}(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n})$, ${\sigma}_{w}$ and $\psi_{\varepsilon}$ be based ring automorphisms of $M_{n,\Gamma({\lambda}),B({\lambda})}$. We define the based poset automorphism ${\beta}^{\lambda}(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n})$ (respectively, ${\sigma}^{\lambda}_{w}$, $\psi^{\lambda}_{\varepsilon}$) of $(\Lambda,\leq,f)$ to be the automorphism that induces the identity map on the underlying poset and on all based rings $f(\mu)$ for $\mu\neq{\lambda}$, and that induces the automorphism ${\beta}(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n})$ (respectively, ${\sigma}_{w}$, $\psi_{\varepsilon}$) on $f({\lambda})$.
Definition Definition 2.2.1 Let $A$ be a tabular algebra with trace, and maintain the usual notation. Define $\widehat{X}:=v^{-{\text{\bf a}}(X)}X$ for any tabular basis element $X\in\text{\rm Im}(C)$. The free ${\Cal{A}}^{-}$-module $A_{\lambda}^{-}$ is defined to be generated by the elements $\{\widehat{X}:X\in{\mathbb{c}}_{\lambda}\}$. We set $t_{X}$ to be the image of $\widehat{X}$ in $A_{\lambda}^{\infty}:={{A_{\lambda}^{-}}\over{v^{-1}A_{\lambda}^{-}}}.$ The latter is a ${\mathbb{Z}}$-algebra with basis $\{t_{X}:X\in{\mathbb{c}}_{\lambda}\}$ and structure constants $t_{X}t_{X^{\prime}}=\sum_{X^{\prime\prime}\in{\mathbb{c}}}{\gamma}_{X,X^{% \prime},X^{\prime\prime}}t_{X^{\prime\prime}},$ where the ${\gamma}_{X,X^{\prime},X^{\prime\prime}}\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ are as in Definition 2.1.1. We also set $A^{\infty}:=\bigoplus_{{\lambda}\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}^{\infty};$ this is a ${\mathbb{Z}}$-algebra with basis $\{t_{X}:X\in\text{\rm Im}(C)\}$.
Definition Definition 4.2.2 Fix a diagram $D$. The integer $t(D)$ is defined to be the number of through strings, i.e., strings joining points in different rows. The involutions $S_{1}(D)$, $S_{2}(D)$ in the symmetric group ${\Cal{S}}(n)$ are defined such that $S_{i}(D)$ interchanges the ends of the joins between points in row $i$, with $i\in\{1,2\}$. Corresponding to these we have subsets $\text{\rm Fix}(S_{i}(D))$ of $\{1,\ldots,n\}$, which are the fixed points of the involutions $S_{i}(D)$. Finally, we have a permutation $w(D)$ in ${\Cal{S}}(t)$, where $t=t(D)$; this is the permutation of $\text{\rm Fix}(S_{1}(D))$ determined by taking the end points of the through strings (regarded as joining from row $2$ to row $1$) in the order determined by taking their starting points in row $2$ in increasing order. (We consider ${\Cal{S}}(0)$ to be the trivial group, in which case $w$ is the identity.) The diagram $D$ is then determined by the triple $[S_{1}(D),S_{2}(D),w(D)]$.
Definition Definition 3.1.1 A based poset is a triple $(\Lambda,\leq,f)$ where $(\Lambda,\leq)$ is a poset and $f$ is a function with the property that for each ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$, $f({\lambda})$ is a based ring. An isomorphism of based posets ${\alpha}:(\Lambda,\leq,f){\ \longrightarrow\ }(\Pi,\leq^{\prime},g)$ is an isomorphism of posets ${\alpha}:(\Lambda,\leq){\ \longrightarrow\ }(\Pi,\leq^{\prime})$ such that for all ${\lambda}\in\Lambda$, ${\alpha}$ induces an isomorphism of based rings ${\alpha}:f({\lambda}){\ \longrightarrow\ }g({\alpha}({\lambda}))$.
Definition 7.2. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category. We say that $\mathbf{A}$ is locally perfect if $\mathbf{A}(A,A^{\prime})$ is a perfect $\mathbf{k}$-module: $\mathbf{A}(A,A^{\prime})\in\mathrm{per}(\mathbf{k})$ for all $A,A^{\prime}\in\mathbf{A}$. We say that $\mathbf{A}$ is smooth if the diagonal bimodule is perfect: $h_{\mathbf{A}}\in\mathrm{per}(\mathbf{A}\otimes^{\mathbb{L}}{\mathbf{A}}^{% \mathrm{op}})$.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category. A right $\mathbf{A}$-dg-module $M\in\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$ is acyclic if $M(A)$ is an acyclic complex for all $A\in\mathbf{A}$. The full dg-subcategory of $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$ of acyclic modules is denoted by $\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$. \nomenclature$\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$The dg-category of acyclic right $\mathbf{A}$-modules, for a given dg-category $\mathbf{A}$
Definition 4.11. A dg-category $\mathbf{A}$ is pretriangulated if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})\hookrightarrow\mathrm{tria}(\mathbf{A})$ is an equivalence; it is triangulated if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})\hookrightarrow\mathrm{per}(\mathbf{A})$ is an equivalence.
Definition 3.1. Let $F\colon{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathrm{op}}\otimes\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ be a dg-functor. An end of $F$ is an object $X_{F}\in\mathbf{B}$ together with closed degree $0$ maps $\varepsilon_{A}\colon X_{F}\to F_{A}^{A}$ for all $A\in\mathbf{A}$, satisfying the following universal property: $\begin{gathered}\displaystyle\xymatrix{X^{\prime}\ar@/_{/}[ddr]_{f_{A^{\prime}% }}\ar@/^{/}[drr]^{f_{A}}\ar@{.>}[dr]|-{f}\\ &\displaystyle X_{F}\ar[d]^{\varepsilon_{A^{\prime}}}\ar[r]_{\varepsilon_{A}}&% \displaystyle F_{A}^{A}\ar[d]^{F^{A}_{h}}\\ &\displaystyle F^{A^{\prime}}_{A^{\prime}}\ar[r]^{F_{A^{\prime}}^{h}}&% \displaystyle F^{A}_{A^{\prime}}\end{gathered}}$ that is, for any $h\in\mathbf{A}(A,A^{\prime})$ the above square with vertex $X_{F}$ is commutative, and for any $X^{\prime}$ together with closed degree $0$ maps $f_{A}\colon X^{\prime}\to F_{A}^{A}$ such that the “curved square” with vertex $X^{\prime}$ is commutative, there exists a unique closed degree $0$ map $f\colon X^{\prime}\to X_{F}$ such that $f_{A}=\varepsilon_{A}f$ for all $A\in\mathbf{A}$.
Definition 4.8. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category, and let $F\in\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$. $F$ is h-injective if, for all $N\in\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$, the complex $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})(N,F)$ is acyclic. This equivalent to requiring that $H^{0}(\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A}))(N,F)=\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{A})(N,F)\cong 0$ for all $N\in\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$. The full dg-subcategory of $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$ of h-injective dg-modules is denoted by $\mathrm{h\textrm{-}inj}(\mathbf{A})$. \nomenclature$\mathrm{h\textrm{-}inj}(\mathbf{A})$The dg-category of h-injective $\mathbf{A}$-dg-modules
Definition 6.2. Let $F\colon\mathbf{A}\rightsquigarrow\mathbf{B}$ and $G\colon\mathbf{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathbf{A}$ be $1$-morphisms in $\mathsf{Bimod}$. We say that $F\dashv G$ ($F$ is left adjoint to $G$) if there exist (closed, degree $0$) $2$-morphisms $\eta\colon h_{\mathbf{A}}\to G\diamond F$ and $\varepsilon\colon F\diamond G\to h_{\mathbf{B}}$ such that the following triangular identities are satisfied: $\displaystyle(F\cong F\diamond h_{\mathbf{A}}\xrightarrow{F\diamond\eta}F% \diamond(G\diamond F)\cong(F\diamond G)\diamond F\xrightarrow{\varepsilon% \diamond F}h_{\mathbf{B}}\diamond F\cong F)=1_{F},$ $\displaystyle(G\cong h_{\mathbf{A}}\diamond G\xrightarrow{\eta\diamond G}(G% \diamond F)\diamond G\cong G\diamond(F\diamond G)\xrightarrow{G\diamond% \varepsilon}G\diamond h_{\mathbf{B}}\cong G)=1_{G}.$ The definition of adjoint $1$-morphisms in $\mathsf{DBimod}$ is analogous (replace $\diamond$ with the derived composition $\diamond^{\mathbb{L}}$).
Definition 3.7. Let $F\colon{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathrm{op}}\otimes\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ and $G\colon\mathbf{B}\to\mathbf{C}$ be dg-functors. Assume that $\left(\int_{A}F(A,A),(\varepsilon_{A})\right)$ is an end of $F$. We say that $G$ preserves the end $\int_{A}F(A,A)$ if $\left(G\left(\int_{A}F(A,A)\right),(G(\varepsilon_{A}))\right)$ is an end of $GF$. Dualising, we directly get the definition of preservation of coends.
Definition 2.6. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category. A left $\mathbf{A}$-dg-module is a dg-functor $\mathbf{A}\to\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{k})$. A right $\mathbf{A}$-dg-module is a dg-functor ${\mathbf{A}}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{k})$. Let $\mathbf{B}$ be another dg-category. A $\mathbf{A}$-$\mathbf{B}$-dg-bimodule is a dg-bifunctor ${\mathbf{B}}^{\mathrm{op}}\otimes\mathbf{A}\to\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf% {k})$.
Definition 4.3. Let $F\in\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$. $F$ is h-projective if, for all $N\in\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$, the complex $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})(F,N)$ is acyclic. This equivalent to requiring that $H^{0}(\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A}))(F,N)=\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{A})(F,N)\cong 0$ for all $N\in\mathrm{Ac}(\mathbf{A})$. The full dg-subcategory of $\mathsf{C}_{\mathrm{dg}}(\mathbf{A})$ of h-projective dg-modules is denoted by $\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{A})$. \nomenclature$\mathrm{h\textrm{-}proj}(\mathbf{A})$The dg-category of h-projective right $\mathbf{A}$-dg-modules
Definition 3.2. Let $F\colon{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathrm{op}}\otimes\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ be a dg-functor. A coend of $F$ is an object $Y_{F}\in\mathbf{B}$ together with closed degree $0$ maps $\eta_{A}\colon F^{A}_{A}\to Y_{F}$ for all $A\in\mathbf{A}$, satisfying the following universal property: $\begin{gathered}\displaystyle\xymatrix{F^{A}_{A^{\prime}}\ar[d]_{F^{h}_{A^{% \prime}}}\ar[r]^{F^{A}_{h}}&\displaystyle F_{A}^{A}\ar[d]_{\eta_{A}}\ar@/^{/}[% ddr]^{g_{A}}&\\ \displaystyle F^{A^{\prime}}_{A^{\prime}}\ar[r]^{\eta_{A^{\prime}}}\ar@/_{/}[% drr]_{g_{A^{\prime}}}&\displaystyle Y_{F}\ar@{.>}[dr]|-{g}&\\ &&\displaystyle Y^{\prime},\end{gathered}}$ that is, for any $h\in\mathbf{A}(A^{\prime},A)$ the above square with vertex $Y_{F}$ is commutative, and for any $Y^{\prime}$ together with closed degree $0$ maps $g_{A}\colon F_{A}^{A}\to Y^{\prime}$ such that the “curved square” with vertex $Y^{\prime}$ is commutative, there exists a unique closed degree $0$ map $g\colon Y_{F}\to Y^{\prime}$ such that $g_{A}=g\eta_{A}$ for all $A\in\mathbf{A}$.
Definition 4.13. Let $F\colon\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{A})\to\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{B})$ be a functor. A (total) left derived functor $\mathbb{L}F$ of $F$ \nomenclature$\mathbb{L}F$The left derived functor of $F$ is a right Kan extension of $\delta_{\mathbf{B}}\circ F$ along $\delta_{\mathbf{A}}$: $\xymatrix{\ar@{}[dr]|{\Uparrow}\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{A})\ar[d]^{\delta_{\mathbf{A% }}}\ar[r]^{F}&\mathsf{K}(\mathbf{B})\ar[d]^{\delta_{\mathbf{B}}}\\ \mathsf{D}(\mathbf{A})\ar@{.>}[r]_{\mathbb{L}F}&\mathsf{D}(\mathbf{B}).}$ Dually, a (total) right derived functor $\mathbb{R}F$ of $F$ \nomenclature$\mathbb{R}F$The right derived functor of $F$ is a left Kan extension of $\delta_{B}\circ F$ along $\delta_{A}$.
Definition 2.9. Let $F\colon\mathbf{A}\leftrightarrows\mathbf{B}\colon G$ be dg-functors. We say that $F$ is a left adjoint of $G$ (and $G$ is a right adjoint of $F$), writing $F\dashv G$, if there is an isomorphism of complexes: $\varphi_{A,B}\colon\mathbf{B}(F(A),B)\xrightarrow{\sim}\mathbf{A}(A,G(B)),$ natural in both $A$ and $B$.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathbf{A}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ be dg-categories. A dg-functor $F$ consists of the following data: • a function $F\colon\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}\to\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{B}$; • for any couple of objects $(A,B)$ of $\mathbf{A}$, a chain map $F=F_{(A,B)}\colon\mathbf{A}(A,B)\to\mathbf{B}(F(A),F(B)),$ subject to the usual associativity and unitality axioms.
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category. The underlying category (resp. the homotopy category) of $\mathbf{A}$ is the category $Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ (resp. $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$) which is defined as follows: • $\operatorname{Ob}Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})=\operatorname{Ob}H^{0}(\mathbf{A})=% \operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$, • $Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})(A,B)=Z^{0}(\mathbf{A}(A,B))$ (respectively $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})(A,B)=H^{0}(\mathbf{A}(A,B))$), for all $A,B\in\mathbf{A}$, with natural compositions and identities.
Definition 2.1. A differential graded (dg-) category $\mathbf{A}$ consists of a set of objects $\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$, a hom-complex $\mathbf{A}(A,B)$ for any couple of objects $A,B$, and (unital, associative) composition chain maps of complexes of $\mathbf{k}$-modules: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\mathbf{A}(B,C)\otimes\mathbf{A}(A,B)&\displaystyle% \to\mathbf{A}(A,C),\\ \displaystyle g\otimes f&\displaystyle\mapsto gf=g\circ f\end{split}$
Definition 4 The prop $\operatorname{\mathsf{Corel}}\operatorname{\mathsf{Mat}}{\mathsf{k}[s,s^{-1}]}$ has as morphisms equivalence classes of jointly-epic cospans in $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mat}}{\mathsf{k}[s,s^{-1}]}$.
Definition 5 A system $(T,W,{\mathscr{B}})$ (or simply the behaviour ${\mathscr{B}}$) is controllable if for all $w_{1},w_{2}\in{\mathscr{B}}$ and all times $\tau$, there exists a time $\tau^{\prime}$ such that there is a trajectory $w\in{\mathscr{B}}$ with $w(t)=\begin{cases}w_{1}(t)&t\leq\tau\\ w_{2}(t-\tau^{\prime})&t\geq\tau^{\prime}.\end{cases}$
Definition 1 The monoidal category $\operatorname{\mathsf{LinRel}}_{\mathsf{k}}$ of $\mathsf{k}$-linear relations has $\mathsf{k}$-vector spaces as objects, and as arrows from $V$ to $W$, linear subspaces of $V\times W$, considered as a $\mathsf{k}$-vector space. Composition is relational, and the monoidal product on both objects and morphisms is direct sum.
Definition 3 A linear time-invariant (LTI) behaviour comprises a domain $(\mathsf{k}^{n})^{\mathbb{Z}}$, a codomain $(\mathsf{k}^{m})^{\mathbb{Z}}$, and a subset ${\mathscr{B}}\subset(\mathsf{k}^{n})^{\mathbb{Z}}\oplus(\mathsf{k}^{m})^{% \mathbb{Z}}$ such that $({\mathbb{Z}},\mathsf{k}^{n}\oplus\mathsf{k}^{m},{\mathscr{B}})$ is a complete, linear, time-invariant dynamical system.
Definition 2 The prop $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mat}}{\mathsf{k}[s,s^{-1}]}$ has as arrows $n\to m$ the $m\times n$-matrices over ${\mathsf{k}[s,s^{-1}]}$. Composition is matrix multiplication, and the monoidal product of $A$ and $B$ is $\left[\begin{smallmatrix}A&0\\ 0&B\end{smallmatrix}\right]$.
Definition 3.3 (strong action of an unbiased monoidal category). Let $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{C}$ be unbiased monoidal categories. A ‘strong action’ of $\mathcal{X}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is a strong monoidal functor $\Gamma\colon\mathcal{X}\rightarrow[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]$, from the unbiased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ to the strict monoidal category $[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]$ of strong monoidal endofunctors on $\mathcal{C}$ and monoidal natural transformations between them, with tensor product given by functor composition in ‘diagram order’. Given an object $X\in\mathcal{X}$, we will denote the corresponding strong monoidal endofunctor $\Gamma(X)\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ by $(-)^{X}\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 4.9 (semidirect products of unbiased monoidal categories). Given a strong or weak action of an unbiased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ on an unbiased monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$, we can define a strong or weak semidirect product, $\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$. If the action is strong, the semidirect product will be an unbiased monoidal category. If the action is weak, the semidirect product will be a lax unbiased monoidal category. In either case, the semidirect product is defined as follows. The underlying category of $\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$ is $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{C}$, and we will denote an object $(X,C)\in\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$ by $\langle X,C\rangle$. We will denote the two projection functors as follows. $\mathcal{X}\xleftarrow{\pi_{\mathcal{X}}}\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}% \xrightarrow{\pi_{\mathcal{C}}}\mathcal{C}$ The tensor product is defined as follows. $\bigotimes_{i}\langle X_{i},C_{i}\rangle=\langle\bigotimes_{i}X_{i},\bigotimes% _{i}C_{i}^{\bigodot_{i^{\prime}}X_{i^{\prime}}}\rangle$ In order to define the unitor and associator, it suffices to define their images under the projection functors. The unitor, $\iota$, is defined as follows. The component $\iota\colon\langle X,C\rangle\rightarrow\bigotimes\langle X,C\rangle$ is the morphism whose images under $\pi_{\mathcal{X}}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{C}}$ are the following pair of morphisms, respectively. $\iota\colon X\rightarrow\bigotimes X$ $\iota\colon C\rightarrow\bigotimes C$ The associator, $\gamma$, is defined as follows. The component $\gamma\colon\bigotimes_{i}\bigotimes_{j}\langle X_{ij},C_{ij}\rangle% \rightarrow\bigotimes_{ij}\langle X_{ij},C_{ij}\rangle$ is the morphism whose images under $\pi_{\mathcal{X}}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{C}}$ are the following pair of morphisms, respectively. $\gamma\colon\bigotimes_{i}\bigotimes_{j}X_{ij}\rightarrow\bigotimes_{ij}X_{ij}$ $\displaystyle\bigotimes_{i}(\bigotimes_{j}C_{ij}^{\bigodot_{j^{\prime}}X_{ij^{% \prime}}})^{\bigodot_{i^{\prime}}\bigotimes_{j}X_{i^{\prime}j}}$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\varphi}\bigotimes_{i}\bigotimes_{j}(C_{ij}^{% \bigodot_{j^{\prime}}X_{ij^{\prime}}})^{\bigodot_{i^{\prime}}\bigotimes_{j}X_{% i^{\prime}j}}$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\gamma}\bigotimes_{ij}(C_{ij}^{\bigodot_{j^{\prime}}% X_{ij^{\prime}}})^{\bigodot_{i^{\prime}}\bigotimes_{j}X_{i^{\prime}j}}$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\psi}\bigotimes_{ij}(C_{ij}^{\bigodot_{j^{\prime}}X_% {ij^{\prime}}})^{\bigodot_{i^{\prime}j}X_{i^{\prime}j}}$
Definition 3.2 (weak action of a biased monoidal category). Let $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{C}$ be biased monoidal categories. A ‘weak action’ of $\mathcal{X}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is an oplax monoidal functor $\Gamma\colon\mathcal{X}\rightarrow[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]_{\text{lax}}$, from the biased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ to the strict monoidal category $[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]_{\text{lax}}$ of lax monoidal endofunctors on $\mathcal{C}$ and monoidal natural transformations between them. Equivalently, this is the same as a weak action in which the structure maps below are not assumed to be invertible. $\varphi^{X}\colon\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}% ^{X}\qquad\varphi^{X}_{B,C}\colon B^{X}\otimes C^{X}\rightarrow(B\otimes C)^{X}$ $\psi_{C}\colon C^{\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}}\rightarrow C\qquad\psi_{C}^{X,Y}% \colon C^{X\otimes Y}\rightarrow(C^{X})^{Y}$
Definition 4.1 (semidirect products of biased monoidal categories). Given a strong or weak action of a biased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ on a biased monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$, we can define a strong or weak semidirect product, $\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$. If the action is strong, the semidirect product will be a biased monoidal category. If the action is weak, the semidirect product will be a skew monoidal category. In either case, the semidirect product is defined as follows. The underlying category of $\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$ is $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{C}$, and we will denote an object $(X,C)\in\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}$ by $\langle X,C\rangle$. We will denote the two projection functors as follows. $\mathcal{X}\xleftarrow{\pi_{\mathcal{X}}}\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}% \xrightarrow{\pi_{\mathcal{C}}}\mathcal{C}$ The monoidal unit is defined as follows. $\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}\ltimes\mathcal{C}}=\langle\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}},% \mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}\rangle$ The tensor product is defined as follows. $\langle X,B\rangle\otimes\langle Y,C\rangle=\langle X\otimes Y,B^{Y}\otimes C\rangle$ In order to define the unitors and associators, it suffices to define their images under the projection functors. The left unitor, $\lambda$, is defined as follows. The component $\lambda_{(X,C)}\colon\langle X,C\rangle\rightarrow\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}% \ltimes\mathcal{C}}\otimes\langle X,C\rangle$ is the morphism whose images under $\pi_{\mathcal{X}}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{C}}$ are the following pair of morphisms, respectively. $X\xrightarrow{\lambda_{X}}\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}\otimes X$ $C\xrightarrow{\lambda_{C}}\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}\otimes C\xrightarrow{% \varphi^{B}\otimes C}\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}^{B}\otimes C$ The right unitor, $\rho$, is defined as follows. The component $\rho_{(X,C)}\colon\langle X,C\rangle\otimes\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}\ltimes% \mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\langle X,C\rangle$ is the morphism whose images under $\pi_{\mathcal{X}}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{C}}$ are the following pair of morphisms, respectively. $X\otimes\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}\xrightarrow{\rho_{X}}X$ $C^{\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}}\otimes\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{C}}\xrightarrow{\psi% _{C}\otimes\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}}C\otimes\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{X}}% \xrightarrow{\rho_{C}}C$ The associator, $\alpha$, is defined as follows. The component $\alpha_{(X,A),(Y,B),(Z,C)}\colon\langle X,A\rangle\otimes(\langle Y,B\rangle% \otimes\langle Z,C\rangle)\rightarrow(\langle X,A\rangle\otimes\langle Y,B% \rangle)\otimes\langle Z,C\rangle$ is the morphism whose images under $\pi_{\mathcal{X}}$ and $\pi_{\mathcal{C}}$ are the following pair of morphisms, respectively. $X\otimes(Y\otimes Z)\xrightarrow{\alpha_{X,Y,Z}}(X\otimes Y)\otimes Z$ $\displaystyle A^{Y\otimes Z}\otimes(B^{Z}\otimes C)$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\psi_{A}^{Y,Z}\otimes(B^{Z}\otimes C)}(A^{Y})^{Z}% \otimes(B^{Z}\otimes C)$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\alpha_{(A^{Y})^{Z},B^{Z},C}}((A^{Y})^{Z}\otimes B^{% Z})\otimes C$ $\displaystyle\xrightarrow{\varphi_{A^{Y},B}^{Z}\otimes C}(A^{Y}\otimes B)^{Z}\otimes C$
Definition 2.1 (endomorphism monoid). Let $C$ be a monoid. The endomorphism monoid of $C$ is the monoid whose elements are monoid homomorphisms from $C$ to $C$, whose identity element is the identity on $C$, and whose product is composition, in ‘diagram order’. Explicitly, this means that for any two endomorphisms, $f$ and $g$, their product in the endomorphism monoid, written $fg$, is the endomorphism $x\mapsto g(f(x))$.
Definition 2.3 (semidirect product of monoids). Given an action of a monoid $X$ on a monoid $C$, we can define a ‘semidirect product’ monoid, $X\ltimes C$, as follows. The underlying set of $X\ltimes C$ is $X\times C$, and we will denote a pair $(x,c)\in X\ltimes C$ by $\langle x,c\rangle$. The unit is defined as follows. $1_{X\ltimes C}=\langle 1_{X},1_{C}\rangle$ The product is defined as follows. $\langle x,b\rangle\langle y,c\rangle=\langle xy,b^{y}c\rangle$
Definition 2.2 (action of a monoid). Let $X$ and $C$ be monoids. A right action (which we will simply refer to as an action) of $X$ on $C$ is a monoid homomorphism from $X$ to the endomorphism monoid of $C$. Given an element $x\in X$, we will denote the corresponding endomorphism on $C$ by $(-)^{x}\colon C\rightarrow C$.
Definition 3.1 (strong action of a biased monoidal category). Let $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{C}$ be biased monoidal categories. A ‘strong action’ of $\mathcal{X}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is a strong monoidal functor $\Gamma\colon\mathcal{X}\rightarrow[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]$, from the biased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ to the strict monoidal category $[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]$ of strong monoidal endofunctors on $\mathcal{C}$ and monoidal natural transformations between them, with tensor product given by functor composition in ‘diagram order’. Given an object $X\in\mathcal{X}$, we will denote the corresponding strong monoidal endofunctor $\Gamma(X)\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ by $(-)^{X}\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.4 (weak action of an unbiased monoidal category). Let $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{C}$ be unbiased monoidal categories. A ‘weak action’ of $\mathcal{X}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is an oplax monoidal functor $\Gamma\colon\mathcal{X}\rightarrow[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]_{\text{oplax}}$, from the unbiased monoidal category $\mathcal{X}$ to the strict monoidal category $[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]_{\text{oplax}}$ of lax monoidal endofunctors on $\mathcal{C}$ and monoidal natural transformations between them. Equivalently, this is the same as a weak action in which the structure maps below are not assumed to be invertible. $\varphi^{X}\colon(\bigotimes_{i}C_{i})^{X}\rightarrow\bigotimes_{i}C_{i}^{X}$ $\psi_{C}\colon C^{\bigotimes_{i}X_{i}}\rightarrow C^{\bigodot_{i}X_{i}}$
2.5 Definition (see [balmerchow]*Definitions 8 and 10). The $p$-dimensional cycle group of $\mathcal{C}$ is defined as $\operatorname{Z}^{\Delta}_{p}(\mathcal{C}):=\operatorname{K_{0}}\left((% \mathcal{C}_{(p)}/\mathcal{C}_{(p-1)})^{\natural}\right)~{}.$ The $p$-dimensional Chow group of $\mathcal{C}$ is defined as $\operatorname{CH}^{\Delta}_{p}(\mathcal{C}):=\operatorname{Z}^{\Delta}_{p}(% \mathcal{C})/j\circ q(\ker(i))~{}.$
2.1 Definition. An essentially small triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$ is called tensor triangulated if it comes equipped with a compatible symmetric monoidal structure $\otimes:\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$, i.e. if the functor $\otimes$ is exact in both variables and the two isomorphisms $\Sigma a\otimes\Sigma b\cong\Sigma(a\otimes\Sigma b)\cong\Sigma^{2}(a\otimes b% )\quad\text{and}\quad\Sigma a\otimes\Sigma b\cong\Sigma(\Sigma a\otimes b)% \cong\Sigma^{2}(a\otimes b)$ differ by a sign $-1$ at most. An essentially small tensor triangulated category is called rigid if there is an exact functor $D:\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathcal{C}$ and a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(a\otimes b,c)\cong\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathcal{C}}(b,D(a)\otimes c)$ for all objects $a,b,c\in\mathcal{C}$. The object $D(a)$ is called the dual of $a$.
2.2 Definition (see [balmerfiltrations]*Definition 3.1). A dimension function on $\mathcal{C}$ is a map $\dim:\operatorname{Spc}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathbb{Z}\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ such that the following two conditions hold: 1. If $Q,P$ are points of $\operatorname{Spc}(\mathcal{C})$ such that $Q\in\overline{\{P\}}$, then $\dim(Q)\leq\dim(P)$. 2. If $Q\in\overline{\{P\}}$ and $\dim(Q)=\dim(P)\in\mathbb{Z}$, then $Q=P$. For a subset $V\subset\operatorname{Spc}(\mathcal{C})$, we define $\dim(V):=\sup\{\dim(P)|P\in V\}$. For every $p\in\mathbb{Z}\cup\{\pm\infty\}$, we define the full subcategory $\mathcal{C}_{(p)}:=\{a\in\mathcal{C}:\dim(\operatorname{supp}(a))\leq p\}~{}.$
2.12 Definition. For a triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$, a triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{L}\subset\mathcal{C}$ is called localizing if it is closed under taking set-indexed coproducts (in $\mathcal{C}$). A thick triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{L}\subset\mathcal{C}$ is called Bousfield if the Verdier quotient functor $\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}/\mathcal{S}$ has a right-adjoint. A Bousfield subcategory $\mathcal{L}\subset\mathcal{C}$ is called smashing if the right-adjoint of the Verdier quotient functor $\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}/\mathcal{S}$ preserves set-indexed coproducts.
3.1 Definition. We define the $p$-dimensional tensor triangular cycle groups of $\mathcal{K}$, relative to the action of $\mathcal{T}$ and the $p$-dimensional tensor triangular Chow groups of $\mathcal{K}$, relative to the action of $\mathcal{T}$ as follows: $\operatorname{Z}^{\Delta}_{p}(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{K}):=\operatorname{K_{0}}% \left((\mathcal{K}_{(p)}/\mathcal{K}_{(p-1)})^{c}\right)$ and $\operatorname{CH}^{\Delta}_{p}(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{K}):=\operatorname{Z}^{% \Delta}_{(p)}(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{K})/j\circ q(\ker(i)).$
2.7 Definition. A triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ is called a compactly-rigidly generated tensor triangulated category if (i) $\mathcal{T}$ is a compactly generated triangulated category. We implicitly assume here that $\mathcal{T}$ has set-indexed coproducts. Note that this implies that $\mathcal{T}$ is not essentially small. (ii) $\mathcal{T}$ is equipped with a compatible closed symmetric monoidal structure $\otimes:\mathcal{T}\times\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}$ with unit object $\mathbb{I}$. Here, a symmetric monoidal structure on $\mathcal{T}$ is closed if for all objects $a\in\mathcal{T}$ the functor $a\otimes-$ has a right adjoint $\underline{\mathrm{hom}}(a,-)$. (iii) $\mathbb{I}$ is compact and all compact objects of $\mathcal{T}$ are rigid. Let $\mathcal{T}^{c}\subset\mathcal{T}$ denote the full subcategory of compact objects of $\mathcal{T}$. Then we require that $\mathbb{I}\in\mathcal{T}^{c}$ and that all objects $a$ of $\mathcal{T}^{c}$ are rigid, i.e. for every object $b\in\mathcal{T}$ the natural map $\underline{\circ}:\underline{\mathrm{hom}}(a,\mathbb{I})\otimes b\cong% \underline{\mathrm{hom}}(a,\mathbb{I})\otimes\underline{\mathrm{hom}}(\mathbb{% I},b)\to\underline{\mathrm{hom}}(a,b)~{},$ is an isomorphism.
2.4 Definition. An additive category $\mathcal{A}$ is called idempotent complete if all idempotent endomorphisms in $\mathcal{A}$ split. Every triangulated category $\mathcal{C}$ admits an exact embedding into its idempotent completion $J:\mathcal{C}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{C}^{\natural}$, where $\mathcal{C}^{\natural}$ is an idempotent complete triangulated category such that every exact functor $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ with $\mathcal{D}$ triangulated and idempotent complete factors uniquely through $J$ (see [balschlichidem]).
2.15 Definition (cf. [stevenson]*Definition 6.1). We say that the action $\ast$ of $\mathcal{T}$ on $\mathcal{K}$ satisfies the local-to-global principle if for each $a$ in $\mathcal{K}$ $\langle a\rangle_{\ast}=\langle\Gamma_{x}a|x\in\operatorname{Spc}(\mathcal{T}^% {c})\rangle_{\ast}$ where for a collection of objects $S\subset\mathcal{K}$ we denote by $\langle S\rangle_{\ast}$ the smallest localizing $\mathcal{T}$-submodule of $\mathcal{K}$ containing $S$.
